Overview¶

The goal of the final project is for you to create a digital analytical edition of a corpus using the tools, practices, and perspectives youve learning in this course. You will select a corpus that has already been digitized and transcribed, parse that into an F-compliant set of tables, and then generate and visualize the results of a series of fitted models. You will also draw some tentative conclusions regarding the linguistic, cultural, psychological, or historical features represented by your corpus. The point of the exercise is to have you work with a corpus through the entire pipeline from ingestion to interpretation.

Specifically, you will acquire a collection of long-form texts and perform the following operations:

  • Convert the collection from their source formats (F0) into a set of tables that conform to the Standard Text Analytic Data Model (F2).
  • Annotate these tables with statistical and linguistic features using NLP libraries such as NLTK (F3).
  • Produce a vector representation of the corpus to generate TFIDF values to add to the TOKEN (aka CORPUS) and VOCAB tables (F4).
  • Model the annotated and vectorized model with tables and features derived from the application of unsupervised methods, including PCA, LDA, and word2vec (F5).
  • Explore your results using statistical and visual methods.
  • Present conclusions about patterns observed in the corpus by means of these operations.

When you are finished, you will make the results of your work available in GitHub (for code) and UVA Box (for data). You will submit to Gradescope (via Canvas) a PDF version of a Jupyter notebook that contains the information listed below.

Late movies are the longest and have the fewest scenes. Early movies have a medium number of scenes and are the shortest. Middle movies have the greatest number of scenes and medium length. Thus, late movies have the longest scenes, while early and middle movies have shorter scenes.

Interpretation (4)¶

Describe something interesting about your corpus that you discovered during the process of completing this assignment.

At a minumum, use 250 words, but you may use more. You may also add images if you'd like.

The purpose of the project was to analyze differences in a selection of seven Wes Anderson scripts. As a fan who has seen all of the movies many times, I had hypothesized that there would be major differences among the films. While some differences did occur, PCA approaches showed close clustering on the first and second components. Thus, my perceived drastic differences may not be as reflected in the text as I had originally thought; however, the differences found were important.

The first difference occurred before any analysis was even done. Just in deciphering the regex codes for scene breaks revealed differences across era. The earlier scripts had very homogenous scene breaks, using mostly INT. and EXT. On the other hand, as time progressed, scripts had increasingly complex scene transitions. Thus, simply by structure of script, we see evolution of writing.

From the DFIDF, we see the most prominent characters. Max, from Rushmore, has the highest DIDF, making him the most prominently featured character. However, I would argue that Bottle Rocket is the most character-driven movie because Dignan and Anthony are in the top 5 and Bob is in the 15 (these are the three main characters of Bottle Rocket).

Sentiment analysis revealed some similarities between groups though their were some obvious outliers. Trust is common across movies, but fear and negative sentiment are also common to the early movies. The most negative movie is Rushmore with high levels of sadness, fear, and anger, and the most positive movie is Asteroid City with high levels of joy, trust, and anticipation.

Since I was interested in differences in era, I looked at mean differences in script length and number of scenes. Interestingly, while middle movies have the most scenes, late movies are the longest and have the fewest scenes. This indicates that scenes are longer in the late movies. Early movies have a medium number of scenes, but are the shortest; and middle movies have the greatest number of scenes, but medium length. Again, this indicates that the early and middle movies have shorter scenes.

In conclusion, although PCA showed many similarities, there were some differences that arose from further analysis. There are differences across era in terms of scene and movie structure, and the role of characters within the movie (i.e., in Bottle Rocket and Rushmore).
